revision.text:
{{italic title}} '''''Adelante''''' (''Forward'') was an [[anarchist]] weekly workers newspaper published from [[Santander, Spain]] 1902-1903.<ref>Garrido Martín, Aurora. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=sT6e7RrY6FMC&pg=PA161 Cantabria 1902-1923: elecciones y partidos políticos]''. [Santander]: Universidad de Cantabria, 1990. p. 161</ref><ref name="s1">Suárez Cortina, Manuel. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=DsycezZFORoC&pg=PA96 Santander hace un siglo]''. [Santander]: Universidad de Cantabria, 2000. pp. 94, 96</ref> The first issue was published on May 1, 1902. The newspaper survived until the end of March 1903. ''Adelante'' was noted for its hostility towards the [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]], expressed through the rivalry with the socialist organ ''[[La Voz del Pueblo]]''.<ref name="s1"/><ref>Baró Pazos, Juan. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=OxKEaTeHJP4C&pg=PA64 Mutua Montañesa, en su primer centenario (1905-2005)]''. Santander: Universidad de Cantabria, 2006. p. 64</ref> In total 42 issues of ''Adelante'' were published.<ref>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=PqMbAQAAMAAJ Revista de fomento social]'', Vol, 30,&nbsp;Eds. 117–120. 1975. p. 407</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}} {{Portal|Anarchism|Spain}}
[[Category:1902 establishments in Spain]] [[Category:1903 disestablishments in Spain]] [[Category:Defunct newspapers of Spain]] [[Category:Media in Santander, Spain]] [[Category:Weekly newspapers published in Spain]] [[Category:Publications established in 1902]] [[Category:Publications disestablished in 1903]] [[Category:Spanish-language newspapers]]
{{spain-newspaper-stub}}

The '''African Company of Merchants''' or '''Company of Merchants Trading to Africa''' was a [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]] [[Chartered Company]] operating from 1752 to 1821 in the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]] area of modern [[Ghana]]. This coastal area was dominated by the indigenous [[Fante people]]. It was established by the [[African Company Act 1750]], and in 1752 replaced the [[Royal African Company]]. The latter had been established in 1660.<ref name="Barbary Captive">{{cite book|last1=Adams|first1=Robert|last2=Adams|first2=Charles|title=The Narrative of Robert Adams, A Barbary Captive: A Critical Edition|date=2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge}}</ref>
The assets of the Royal African Company were transferred to the new company and consisted primarily of nine trading posts or [[factory (trading post)|factories]]: [[Fort William, Ghana|Fort William]], [[Fort James (Ghana)|Fort James]], [[Fort Sekondi]], [[Fort Winneba]], [[Fort Apollonia]], [[Fort Tantumquery]], [[Fort Metal Cross]], [[Fort Komenda]], and [[Cape Coast Castle]], the last of which was the administrative centre.<ref name="Barbary Captive"/>
==African Committee== The Company was managed by the African Committee, which was composed of nine committee members, three each from [[London]], [[Liverpool]] and [[Bristol]]. These were elected from the general body of traders from these cities, who paid 40 shillings to be admitted to the company. The company was funded by an annual grant approved by parliament, which covered the costs of the London office and the forts. The Committee had to report to the [[Exchequer]], the [[Admiralty]] and, from 1782, the [[Secretary at War]].<ref name="Barbary Captive"/> [[John Shoolbred]] [[FRSE]] was secretary to the committee for several years.
In 1807, the Imperial government prohibited the African slave trade after 1807, although the Company continued to operate for some years afterwards. In keeping with the ethos of liberal reform, administrative authority over the African Company's territory was transferred to Governor [[Charles MacCarthy (governor)|Charles MacCarthy]] of [[Sierra Leone]], Sierra Leone having been founded as a refuge colony for freed slaves. (Governor McCarthy was subsequently killed in the First [[Anglo-Asante War]].) In 1817, the Company signed a treaty of friendship recognising the [[Asante Empire|Asante]] claims to sovereignty over large areas of the coast, including areas claimed by the Fante. However, after it became public knowledge that Company had failed to suppress the African slave trade within its privately held territory, the British government abolished the Company once and for all in 1821. Slavery as an institution, however, continued to exist throughout the British Empire until 1834.
