{{expand language|topic=|langcode=ru|otherarticle=Александропольский уезд|date=April 2017}} {{Infobox Russian governorate |EnglishName = Aleksandropolsky Uyezd |RussianName = Александропольский уезд |RussianOldName = |LocatorMap = Erivan Governorate Aleksandropolsky uezd.svg |CoatOfArms = Coat of Arms of Erivan gubernia (Russian empire).png |CoatOfArmsLink = Coat of arms of Erivan Governorate |AdmCtrName = [[Gyumri|Aleksandropol]] |FoundationDate = 1849 |AbolishmentDate = 1918 |PoliticalStatus = Uyezd |PoliticalStatusLink = Uyezd |Region = Caucasus |Area = 3759.8 |Population = 165503 |UrbanPopulation = |RuralPopulation = |CensusYear = 1897 |GovAsOf = 1918 |HeadTitle = |HeadName = Governor of Aleksandropolsky Uyezd }} The '''Aleksandropolsky Uyezd''' ({{lang-ru|Александропольский уезд}}; {{lang-hy|Ալեքսանդրապոլի գավառ}}) was a [[counties of the Russian Empire|county]] of the [[Erivan Governorate]] of the [[Caucasus Viceroyalty (1801–1917)|Caucasus Viceroyalty]] of the [[Russian Empire]]. It bordered the governorate's [[Echmiadzinsky Uyezd|Echmiadzinsky]] and [[Novobayazetsky Uyezd]]s to the south, the [[Borchalinsky Uyezd]] of the [[Tiflis Governorate]] to the north and east, the [[Kazakhsky Uyezd]] of the [[Elisabethpol Governorate]] to the southeast, and the [[Kars Oblast]] to the west. It included most of the [[Shirak Province]] and southern parts of the [[Lori Province]] of present-day northern [[Armenia]]. Its administrative center was Aleksandropol ([[Gyumri]]).<ref>{{cite book|last=Tsutsiev|first=Arthur|translator=Nora Seligman Favorov|title=Atlas of the Ethno-Political History of the Caucasus|year=2014|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven|isbn=9780300153088|page=59}}</ref>
==Demographics== According to the 1897 [[Russian Empire Census]], the population of the district was 165,503, the overwhelming majority of which were [[Armenians]] (85.5%). Minorities included Tatars (modern [[Azerbaijanis]]; 4.7%), [[East Slavs]] ([[Russians]], [[Ukrainians]], and [[Belarusians]]; 4%), [[Kurds]] (3%), [[Greeks]] (0.6%), and [[Poles]] (0.5%).<ref>{{ru icon}} [http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/emp_lan_97_uezd.php?reg=572 1897 Census, Aleksandropolsky Uyezd] ''Demoscope Weekly''</ref> The largest city in the district was Aleksandropol, which had a total population of 30,616, of which 21,771 (71%) were Armenians, 5,157 (16.8%) East Slavs, 1,090 (3.5%) Tatars, 921 (3%) Poles, 415 (1%) [[Jews]], 316 (1%) [[Lithuanians]], and 266 (0.8%) Greeks.<ref>{{ru icon}} [http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/emp_lan_97_uezd.php?reg=573 1897 Census, Aleksandropol City] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025103210/http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/emp_lan_97_uezd.php?reg=573 |date=2014-10-25 }} ''Demoscope Weekly''</ref>
