{{distinguish|National Union (Chad)}}
{{Politics of Chad}}

The '''Chadian National Union''' ({{lang-fr|Union Nationale Tchadienne}}, UNT) was a radical Muslim political party in [[Chad]].

==History==
The party was founded in 1958 by Issa Dana, Mahamut Outman and [[Abba Siddick]]. Created to lobby the "no" vote to the [[Chadian constitutional referendum, 1958|referendum]] on Chad's entry in the [[French Community]], the party advocated drastic political reforms, to be achieved if necessary through violence. The party was banned in 1962 when the president [[François Tombalbaye]] proclaimed the [[Chadian Progressive Party]] sole legal party. It survived as a clandestine organization under the leadership of [[Ibrahim Abatcha]].

In 1966 the party merged with the General Union of the Children of Chad to form the [[FROLINAT|National Liberation Front of Chad]] (FROLINAT).<ref>[http://www.content.eisa.org.za/old-page/chad-defunct-parties Chad: Defunct parties] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409055303/http://www.content.eisa.org.za/old-page/chad-defunct-parties |date=April 9, 2015 }} EISA</ref>

