'''Dinguiraye''' is a small town in northern [[Guinea]], known for its large [[mosque]] which until recently was [[thatched]]. As of 2014 it had a population of 47,250 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geohive.com/cntry/guinea.aspx |title=Guinea |publisher=Institut National de la Statistique, Guinea, accessed via Geohive |accessdate=27 August 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124030052/http://www.geohive.com/cntry/guinea.aspx |archivedate=24 November 2015 |df= }}</ref>
==History== [[File:Mosquée de Dinguiraye.jpg|thumb|left|Mosquée de Dinguiraye ca. 1900]] The town and its mosque hold special historical importance; [[El Hadj Umar Tall]] founded the [[Toucouleur Empire]] in the city and initially made it his capital. Al-Hadj Umar also built the city's large mosque at this time and the city served as a staging ground for his 1850 jihad.<ref>Histoire d'Afrique: les enjeux de mémoire, Jean-Pierre Chrétien, Jean-Louis Triaud KARTHALA Editions, 1. jan. 1999, pg.73</ref>
==Notable people== *[[Saïdou Bokoum]] (1945-) - writer
