{{italic title}} {{Refimprove|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox book | name = In the Eyes of Mr Fury | image = In the Eyes of Mr Fury Cover.jpg | caption = Cover of first edition, designed by the Senate fiction from photography by Ewan Fraser. | author = [[Philip Ridley]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | series = | genre = [[Gay literature]], [[Coming-of-age story]], [[Magic Realism]], [[Mystery novel]] | publisher = | release_date = 1989 (revised version 2016) | media_type = | pages = | isbn = }} '''''In the Eyes of Mr Fury ''''' is a [[Gay literature|gay]], [[Coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]], [[magic realist]],<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Schimel |editor-first=Lawrence |editor-link= Lawrence Schimel |title=Things Invisible to See: Gay and Lesbian Tales of Magical Realism|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UCtJUCkRenoC&pg=RA1-PA5&dq=lawrence+schimel+things+invisible+to+see&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEkrOhqfPMAhUhKMAKHbKvC38Q6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=philip%20ridley&f=false|date=September 1998 |publisher=Circlet Press |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |isbn=9781885865229 |page=11 |chapter=Introduction by [[Lawrence Schimel]]}}</ref> [[mystery novel]] by [[Philip Ridley]]. It was Ridley's first novel to be published, previously having his novella ''Crocodilia'' released in 1988. It was also the first book published in the [[Penguin Books]] Originals list.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} The novel has become a [[cult classic]] and became something of an underground phenomenon when published in Russia in 2004.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
In 2015 It was announced that the novel was to be reissued by [[Valancourt Books]] along with Ridley's other gay themed literature for adults ''Crocodilia'' and ''[[Flamingoes in Orbit]]''.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=Valancourt_B|author=Valancourt Books|number=596800145674661889|date=8 May 2015|title=Philip Ridley's IN THE EYES OF MR FURY. Incredible book. Huge thanx @ethereallad for introducing us to it. New cover:}}</ref> It was later revealed in 2016 that the novel had been fully revised by Ridley and is almost double the length of the original edition, with Valancourt Books stating on their website that "Ridley has reimagined the story, expanding the original short novel into the world’s first [[LGBT literature|LGBT]] magical realist epic" and that the new edition is "a vast, labyrinthine, hall-of-mirrors saga... covering over a hundred years."<ref name=Valancourt>{{cite web|title=In the Eyes of Mr Fury (1989)|url=http://www.valancourtbooks.com/in-the-eyes-of-mr-fury-1989.html|website=www.valancourtbooks.com|publisher=[[Valancourt Books]]|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> This new edition was released on 6 December 2016<ref>{{cite web|title=In the Eyes of Mr Fury (Paperback)|url=http://www.foyles.co.uk/witem/fiction-poetry/in-the-eyes-of-mr-fury,philip-ridley-9781943910373|website=www.foyles.co.uk|publisher=W&G Foyle Ltd|accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> and later made into an [[audiobook]] that was released on [[iTunes]] and [[Audible (store)|Audible]] in late 2017.<ref name=Valancourt/>
==In Other Media==
*The song ''[[Fury Eyes]]'' from [[The Creatures]]' second album, ''[[Boomerang (The Creatures album)|Boomerang]]'' is dedicated to the novel.<ref>Peter Buckley (2003). ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Fie47qSuTsoC&pg=PA1800&lpg=PA1800&dq=Fury+Eyes+song+Philip+Ridley&source=bl&ots=c-OdaRrz27&sig=5jvSf_mzmOpA7936Q2S_8NGxVn8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBWoVChMIo_XLpZyuxwIVCtkaCh0Pjgld#v=onepage&q&f=false The Rough Guide to Rock]''. Rough Guides. {{ISBN|1858284570}}. Pages 247.</ref>
