{{Infobox company |logo= PIL logo2.jpeg |image= Kota Lambai (ship, 2008) 001.jpg |caption= The [[container ship]] ''Kota Lambai'', one of Pacific International Lines' ships |type= |foundation= 1967 |location=[[Singapore]] |locations= |area_served= |industry=[[Transport]] |products = |num_employees= 18,000 |homepage= www.pilship.com |name = Pacific International Lines }}
'''Pacific International Lines''' ('''PIL''') is a [[shipping company]] incorporated in [[Singapore]] in 1967. The founder of PIL is the Chinese entrepreneur [[Chang Yun Chung]].
==Description== The company originally operated only two ships, but constantly expanded to finally celebrate its first 50 years of history in 2017, and ranking within the first 10 largest container shipping lines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://alphaliner.axsmarine.com/PublicTop100/|title=PublicTop100|website=Alphaliner.axsmarine.com|accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref>
The fleet is composed of 160 vessels with a capacity of 447,000 TEUs, while waiting for additional 13 new ships to be delivered within end of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.portcalls.com/pil-takes-delivery-11800teu-box-ships/|title=PIL takes delivery of 11,800-TEU box ships - PortCalls Asia - Asian Shipping and Maritime News|website=Portcalls.com|accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref> It employs over 18,000 staff globally, regularly serving about 500 ports in nearly 100 countries worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/pil-ready-to-move-up-to-become-b-division-player|title=PIL ready to move up to become 'B-division' player|date=16 March 2017|website=Straitstimes.com|accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref>
As forerunner in IT improvements, '''PIL''' has implemented a [[blockchain]] supply platform to share established data with [[DP World]] - [[Port of Singapore]] via [[IBM]] systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/245431/pil-psa-ibm-conclude-blockchain-trial-from-chongqing-to-singapore/|title=PIL, PSA, IBM Conclude Blockchain Trial from Chongqing to Singapore|website=Worldmaritimenews.com|accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref>
In 2017 PIL and [[COSCO]] have entered into a mutual chartering agreement, to supply and exchange vessels during shipping demand peak times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hellenicshippingnews.com/cosco-shipping-announces-chartering-agreement-with-pil/|title=Cosco Shipping Announces Chartering Agreement with PIL - Hellenic Shipping News Worldwide|website=Hellenicshippingnews.com|accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref>
In March 2015, PIL partially took over the ownership of Singapore's [[Mariana Express Lines]] (MELL). According to the deal, PIL has assumed the majority shareholding. Since then, MELL has continued to operate under its own brand and pre-existing business, as agreed internally at the time of the purchase.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/155661/pil-takes-majority-stake-in-mariana-express-lines/|title=PIL Takes Majority Stake in Mariana Express Lines|website=Worldmaritimenews.com|accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref>
